{
  "answer": "**Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1**\n\nThe *Āṅgirasa Smṛti* sets out escalating penalties for a Brahmin whose top-knot (*śikhā*) is damaged or severed, treating it as essential to Brahminhood alongside the sacred thread.[^1] For a single cutting by an enemy, \"he should immediately wear hair from a cow's tail on his ear and, being pure, should perform a Prājāpatya penance.\"[^2] If \"the top-knot is cut in the middle, he is purified by a Prājāpatya penance.\"[^3] However, \"If the top-knot is cut by enemies five times, his Brahminhood is lost, even with a new *saṃskāra*.\"[^4]\n\n[^1]: /works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-54d41e\n[^2]: /works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-94f7a6\n[^3]: /works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-6dc072\n[^4]: /works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-f210ca  \n(Note: *Ang_1.65* spans these paragraphs for full context.)",
